---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Theoretical Framework"
  description="The philosophical constellation guiding Nicholas Daly's doctoral research"
  section="research"
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 style="font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem); font-weight: 400; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
        The Philosophical <em style="color: var(--red); font-style: italic;">Constellation</em>
      </h1>
      <div class="page-hero-sub">
        Eight foundational thinkers who illuminate the path between imagination, technology, and pedagogy.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FRAMEWORK -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="drop-cap prose" style="max-width: var(--max-width);">
        The theoretical framework that structures this research is not a linear argument but a constellation of eight philosophical positions, each illuminating different facets of the central question: How can we teach composition in ways that honor both human creativity and technological possibility?
      </p>

      <ul class="framework-list">
        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Corbin</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Henry Corbin: Mundus Imaginalis</strong><br>
            The imaginal world is not fantasy but an actual realm of knowledge, a faculty of perception distinct from both material reality and abstract intellection. For Corbin, the imagination is where spirit becomes visible and where meaning takes form. Applied to composition pedagogy: the student's inner imaginative life is not decoration added to technical skill, but the very ground of authentic musical thinking. The Bestiary works in the imaginal register, inviting students to engage creatures as real teachers rather than mere metaphors.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Stiegler</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Bernard Stiegler: Pharmakon</strong><br>
            Technology is fundamentally ambivalent—it is simultaneously poison and cure, pharmaka. Tools like writing, recording, and now algorithms can either deskill us (pharmakon as poison) or open new possibilities for thought and creation (pharmakon as medicine). The key is maintaining collective attention and intentionality. Composition pedagogy must grapple with how digital tools shape student thinking, neither rejecting technology nor surrendering agency to it.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Biesta</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Gert Biesta: Subjectification</strong><br>
            Education has three purposes: qualification (skill development), socialization (cultural transmission), and subjectification (becoming a unique subject). Most pedagogy overemphasizes the first two, treating students as vessels to fill. True education makes space for subjectification—the emergence of the student as an irreducible voice. Composition teaching should cultivate conditions where the student's unique sensibility can emerge, not homogenize everyone into a single aesthetic.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Illich</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Ivan Illich: Convivial Tools</strong><br>
            Convivial tools are those that enhance human agency rather than diminish it, that can be controlled by users rather than controlling users. Schools often institutionalize learning in ways that diminish conviviality; by contrast, a "convivial" tool for composition would invite interaction, allow for surprise, and place agency in the learner's hands. The Bestiary aims to be a convivial tool—one that students can appropriate and improvise with rather than passively consuming.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Ong</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Walter Ong: Orality-Literacy</strong><br>
            Ong's analysis of how writing and print transformed consciousness applies equally to music technology. Oral cultures transmit music through embodied apprenticeship; literate cultures use notation. Digital culture creates new modalities. Understanding these shifts is essential for designing pedagogy that acknowledges what is gained and lost with each technological transition. The Bestiary exists at the intersection of oral, notated, and algorithmic transmission.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Abram</div>
          <div>
            <strong>David Abram: Ecophenomenology</strong><br>
            Abram argues that the more-than-human world (animals, plants, landscape) is not background but participant in meaning-making. For a musician, this opens onto ecocritical listening—hearing the voices of nature in our compositions, understanding human music as part of a larger ecological chorus. Many of the Bestiary creatures draw on natural patterns and ecological principles, grounding compositional practice in our interdependence with the living world.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Bakhtin</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Mikhail Bakhtin: Chronotope</strong><br>
            Bakhtin's concept of the chronotope—the inseparability of time and space in narrative—proves generative for understanding musical form. Every musical gesture carries implicit references to genres, periods, cultural contexts. A composition is always dialogic, responding to and remixing voices from musical history. Pedagogically, this means teaching students to hear their own compositional choices as participating in ongoing conversation across genres and periods.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Frayling-Borgdorff</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Christopher Frayling & Henk Borgdorff: Artistic Research</strong><br>
            Artistic research is research *through* creative practice rather than about it. Knowledge is embodied in the artwork itself, not merely expressed through it. This framework legitimizes the Bestiary as a primary research output—not merely an illustration of theoretical ideas, but a knowledge-making artifact. The compositions, algorithms, and creatures produce knowledge about pedagogy that cannot be articulated propositionally.
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">✦ ✦ ✦</div>

  <!-- ADJACENT THINKERS -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 500; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--ink);">Adjacent Thinkers</h2>

      <p style="color: var(--ink-light); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Beyond the eight core theorists, the research engages with several others who illuminate specific dimensions:
      </p>

      <ul class="framework-list">
        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Gordon</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Douglas Kahn & Nigel Thrift: Sonic Culture</strong><br>
            Kahn's "earth sound full" and approaches to sound studies that decentre human listening expand what we consider "music" and who gets to be a composer.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Oliveros</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Pauline Oliveros: Deep Listening</strong><br>
            Oliveros's practice of deep listening and meditation in composition provides an experiential pedagogy that complements the Bestiary's imaginal approach. Her emphasis on listening as an ethical and transformative practice is central to how students should approach algorithmic composition.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Schafer</div>
          <div>
            <strong>R. Murray Schafer: Soundscape Ecology</strong><br>
            Schafer's concept of soundscape as a living ecosystem and his World Soundscape Project establish that composition happens within an ecological context. The student composer is not creating in isolation but participating in the sonic life of the world.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Solnit</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Rebecca Solnit: Hope and Maps</strong><br>
            Solnit's work on hope as a practice and her meditation on navigation and cartography inform the Bestiary's framing as an imaginal atlas. How do we map territories we cannot see? How does hope survive in difficulty?
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Johnston</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Ben Johnston: Microtonal Pedagogy</strong><br>
            Johnston's experimental approach to tuning and his insistence on expanding the palette of what is "musical" provide a compositional model for how pedagogy can honor students' experimentation and creative risks.
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="framework-item">
          <div class="framework-label">Partch</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Harry Partch: Instrument Design & Pedagogy</strong><br>
            Partch's design of new instruments and his accompanying pedagogical writings demonstrate that constraining the musical palette can paradoxically expand creative possibility. The Bestiary works similarly—each creature operates with specific constraints that generate distinctive possibilities.
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
